responded: The root cause of the use-after-free is that in the function `dom_document_save_xml`, the `intern` pointer and its members (especially `intern->document`) may point to already-freed memory if the object backing `ZEND_THIS` has already been destroyed as part of PHP object lifecycle. From the free path, we see that the internals (including the `document`) will be freed during `dom_objects_free_storage`, which NULLs `intern->ptr` but doesn't NULL out `intern->document`, which is dangerous. Other parts of the code (notably `php_libxml_decrement_doc_ref`) do set their internal pointers to NULL after freeing, but not universally.

**A safe, targeted patch** is to NULL `intern->document` and `intern->ptr` after freeing the related memory in `dom_objects_free_storage()`. This will prevent a stale pointer dereference in later DOM method calls, which is the likely cause of the use-after-free.

Here’s the patch:

args.patch:
--- a/ext/dom/php_dom.c
+++ b/ext/dom/php_dom.c
@@ -1444,13 +1444,14 @@
 	php_libxml_node_ptr *ptr = intern->ptr;
 	if (ptr != NULL && ptr->node != NULL) {
 		xmlNodePtr node = ptr->node;

 		if (node->type != XML_DOCUMENT_NODE && node->type != XML_HTML_DOCUMENT_NODE) {
 			php_libxml_node_decrement_resource((php_libxml_node_object *) intern);
 		} else {
 			php_libxml_decrement_node_ptr((php_libxml_node_object *) intern);
 			php_libxml_decrement_doc_ref((php_libxml_node_object *) intern);
 		}
-		intern->ptr = NULL;
+		intern->ptr = NULL;
+		intern->document = NULL;
 	}
 }

